<p>The <b>kelvin</b> (symbol: <b>K</b>) is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/SI_base_unit" title=3D"SI base unit">base unit</a> for <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temperature" title=3D"Temperature">temper=
ature</a> in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Sys=
tem_of_Units" title=3D"International System of Units">International System =
of Units</a> (SI). The <b>Kelvin scale</b> is an <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Absolute_scale" title=3D"Absolute scale">absolute</a> <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temperature_scale" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Temperature scale">temperature scale</a> that starts at the lowes=
t possible temperature (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absolute_z=
ero" title=3D"Absolute zero">absolute zero</a>), taken to be 0&nbsp;K.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-MEP_for_kelvin_2019_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-MEP_for_kelvin_2019-1"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-SI_Brochure_9_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-SI_Brochure_9-2"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-BIPM_web_page_for_kelvin_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-BIPM_web_page_for_kelvin-3"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST_SI_redefinition_4-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-NIST_SI_redefin=
ition-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> By definition, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Celsius" title=3D"Celsius">Celsius</a> scale (symbol =C2=B0C) and the =
Kelvin scale have the exact same magnitude; that is, a rise of 1&nbsp;K is =
equal to a rise of 1&nbsp;=C2=B0C and vice versa, and any temperature in de=
grees Celsius can be converted to kelvin by adding 273.15.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-MEP_for_kelvin_2019_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-MEP_for_kelvin_2019-1"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-nist_intro_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-nist_intro-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The 19th century British scientist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Lord_Kelvin" title=3D"Lord Kelvin">Lord Kelvin</a> first developed =
and proposed the scale.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nist_intro_5-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-nist_intro-5"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> It was often called the "absolute Celsius" scale in the early 2=
0th century.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-absoluteC_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-absoluteC-6"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
The kelvin was formally added to the International System of Units in 1954,=
 defining 273.16&nbsp;K to be the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Triple_point_of_water" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Triple point of water=
">triple point of water</a>. The Celsius, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Fahrenheit" title=3D"Fahrenheit">Fahrenheit</a>, and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rankine_scale" title=3D"Rankine scale">Rankine</=
a> scales were redefined in terms of the Kelvin scale using this definition=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SI_Brochure_9_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-SI_Brochure_9-2"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-Busting_Myths_about_the_Metric_System_7-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-Busting_Myths_=
about_the_Metric_System-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST_HB44_Appendix=
_C_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin=
#cite_note-NIST_HB44_Appendix_C-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/2019_revision_of_the_SI" title=3D"2019 revision of the SI">=
2019 revision of the SI</a> now defines the kelvin in terms of energy by se=
tting the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boltzmann_constant" titl=
e=3D"Boltzmann constant">Boltzmann constant</a>; every 1&nbsp;K change of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermodynamic_temperature" title=3D=
"Thermodynamic temperature">thermodynamic temperature</a> corresponds to a =
change in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermal_energy" titl=
e=3D"Thermal energy">thermal energy</a>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i><s=
ub>B</sub><i>T</i></span>, of <i>exactly</i> <span class=3D"nowrap"><span d=
ata-sort-value=3D"6977138064900000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.380<span style=3D"=
margin-left:.25em;">649</span><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-righ=
t:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9223</sup>&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joules" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Joules">joules</=
a></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SI_Brochure_9_2-2" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-SI_Brochure_9-2"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
