<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKelvin&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermodynamic_temperatur=
e#History" title=3D"Thermodynamic temperature">Thermodynamic temperature =
=C2=A7&nbsp;History</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Precursors">Precursors</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKelvin&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Precursors"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Melting_ice_thermometer.jpg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/6/64/Melting_ice_thermometer.jpg/250px-Melting_ice_thermometer.jpg" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"217" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"2536" data-file-height=3D"2204"></a><figcaption>An ice water=
 bath offered a practical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calibrat=
ion" title=3D"Calibration">calibration</a> point for <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermometers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Thermometer=
s">thermometers</a> (shown here in Celsius) before the physical nature of h=
eat was well understood.</figcaption></figure>
<p>During the 18th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conver=
sion_of_scales_of_temperature" title=3D"Conversion of scales of temperature=
">multiple temperature scales</a> were developed,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST_k=
elvin_history_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-NIST_kelvin_history-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> notably <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fahrenheit" title=3D"Fahrenheit">Fahrenheit</=
a> and centigrade (later Celsius). These scales predated much of the modern=
 science of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermodynamics" title=
=3D"Thermodynamics">thermodynamics</a>, including <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Atomic theory=
">atomic theory</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kineti=
c_theory_of_gases" title=3D"Kinetic theory of gases">kinetic theory of gase=
s</a> which underpin the concept of absolute zero. Instead, they chose defi=
ning points within the range of human experience that could be reproduced e=
asily and with reasonable accuracy, but lacked any deep significance in the=
rmal physics. In the case of the Celsius scale (and the long defunct <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton_scale" title=3D"Newton scale">New=
ton</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R%C3%A9aumur_scale" ti=
tle=3D"R=C3=A9aumur scale">R=C3=A9aumur scales</a>) the melting point of ic=
e served as such a starting point, with Celsius being defined (from the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1740s" title=3D"1740s">1740s</a> to t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1940s" title=3D"1940s">1940s</a=
>) by calibrating a thermometer such that:
</p>
<ul><li>Water's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freezing_point" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Freezing point">freezing point</a> is 0&nbsp;=
=C2=B0C.</li>
<li>Water's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boiling_point" title=
=3D"Boiling point">boiling point</a> is 100&nbsp;=C2=B0C.</li></ul>
<p>This definition assumes pure water at a specific <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure" title=3D"Pressure">pressure</a> chosen to appro=
ximate the natural air pressure at sea level. Thus, an increment of 1&nbsp;=
=C2=B0C equals <span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span cl=
ass=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">100=
</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> of the temperature difference between the me=
lting and boiling points. The same temperature interval was later used for =
the Kelvin scale.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Charles's_law"><span id=3D"=
Charles.27s_law"></span>Charles's law</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DKelvin&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=
=3D"Edit section: Charles's law"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>From 1787 to 1802, it was determined by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Jacques_Charles" title=3D"Jacques Charles">Jacques Charles</a> (un=
published), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Dalton" title=3D"=
John Dalton">John Dalton</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dalton_1801_1_10-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-Da=
lton_1801_1-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dalton_1801_2_11-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-Dalto=
n_1801_2-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josep=
h_Louis_Gay-Lussac" title=3D"Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac">Joseph Louis Gay-Luss=
ac</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gay-Lussac_1802_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-Gay-Lussac_1802-12"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> that, at constant pressure, ideal gases expanded or contracted thei=
r volume linearly (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles%27s_law=
" title=3D"Charles's law">Charles's law</a>) by about 1/273 parts per degre=
e Celsius of temperature's change up or down, between 0&nbsp;=C2=B0C and 10=
0&nbsp;=C2=B0C. Extrapolation of this law suggested that a gas cooled to ab=
out =E2=88=92273&nbsp;=C2=B0C would occupy zero volume.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Lord_Kelvin">Lord Kelvin</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKelvin&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Lord Kelvin"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
