<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"First_absolute_scale">First=
 absolute scale</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DKelvin&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: First =
absolute scale"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>In 1848, William Thomson, who was later <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Nobility" title=3D"Nobility">ennobled</a> as <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lord_Kelvin" title=3D"Lord Kelvin">Lord Kelvin</a>, pub=
lished a paper <i>On an Absolute Thermometric Scale</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-FOOTNOTEThomson1882100=E2=80=93106_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEThomson1882100%E2%80%9=
3106-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> The scale proposed in the paper turned out to be unsat=
isfactory, but the principles and formulas upon which the scale was based w=
ere correct.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Magie_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-Magie-14"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For ex=
ample, in a footnote, Thomson derived the value of =E2=88=92273&nbsp;=C2=B0=
C for absolute zero by calculating the negative reciprocal of 0.00366=E2=80=
=94the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermal_expansion#Isobaric_=
expansion_in_ideal_gases" title=3D"Thermal expansion">coefficient of therma=
l expansion</a> of an ideal gas per degree Celsius relative to the ice poin=
t.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This derived value agrees with=
 the currently accepted value of =E2=88=92273.15&nbsp;=C2=B0C, allowing for=
 the precision and uncertainty involved in the calculation.
</p><p>The scale was designed on the principle that "a unit of heat descend=
ing from a body <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A=
</span> at the temperature <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">T</span>=C2=B0 of this scale, to a body <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span> at the temperature <span class=3D=
"nowrap">(<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">T</span=
> =E2=88=92 1)=C2=B0</span>, would give out the same mechanical effect, wha=
tever be the number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">T</span>."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEThomson1882104_16-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-FOOTNOTETh=
omson1882104-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Specifically, Thomson expressed the amount of =
work necessary to produce a unit of heat (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Thermal_efficiency" title=3D"Thermal efficiency">thermal effici=
ency</a>) as <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span=
