>
</p><p>This definition by itself is not sufficient. Thomson specified that =
the scale should have two properties:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEThomson188=
2235_32-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kel=
vin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEThomson1882235-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>The absolute values of two temperatures are to one another in the p=
roportion of the heat taken in to the heat rejected in a perfect thermodyna=
mic engine working with a source and refrigerator at the higher and lower o=
f the temperatures respectively.</li>
<li>The difference of temperatures between the freezing- and boiling-points=
 of water under standard atmospheric pressure shall be called 100 degrees. =
(The same increment as the Celsius scale) Thomson's best estimates at the t=
ime were that the temperature of freezing water was 273.7&nbsp;K and the te=
mperature of boiling water was 373.7&nbsp;K.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTETho=
mson1882236_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Kelvin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEThomson1882236-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>These two properties would be featured in all future versions of the Kel=
vin scale, although it was not yet known by that name. In the early decades=
 of the 20th century, the Kelvin scale was often called the "absolute <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celsius_scale" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Celsius scale">Celsius</a>" scale, indicating Celsius degrees counte=
d from absolute zero rather than the freezing point of water, and using the=
 same symbol for regular Celsius degrees, =C2=B0C.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-absol=
uteC_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelv=
in#cite_note-absoluteC-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Triple_point_standard">Trip=
le point standard</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DKelvin&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Trip=
le point standard"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size skin-invert-image" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Phase-diag2.svg" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/3/34/Phase-diag2.svg/500px-Phase-diag2.svg.png" decoding=3D"async=
" width=3D"380" height=3D"318" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D=
"530" data-file-height=3D"443"></a><figcaption>A typical <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_diagram" title=3D"Phase diagram">phase diagram=
</a>. The solid green line applies to most substances; the dashed green lin=
e gives the anomalous behavior of water. The boiling line (solid blue) runs=
 from the triple point to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crit=
ical_point_(thermodynamics)" title=3D"Critical point (thermodynamics)">crit=
ical point</a>, beyond which further increases in temperature and pressure =
produce a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercritical_fluid" tit=
le=3D"Supercritical fluid">supercritical fluid</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In 1873, William Thomson's older brother <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/James_Thomson_(engineer)" title=3D"James Thomson (engineer)">Jame=
s</a> coined the term <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triple_po=
int" title=3D"Triple point">triple point</a></i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-=
34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> to describe the combination of temperature and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure" title=3D"Pressure">pressure</a> at w=
hich the solid, liquid, and gas <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ph=
ase_(matter)" title=3D"Phase (matter)">phases</a> of a substance were capab=
le of coexisting in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermodynamic_=
equilibrium" title=3D"Thermodynamic equilibrium">thermodynamic equilibrium<=
/a>. While any two phases could coexist along a range of temperature-pressu=
re combinations (e.g. the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boiling_=
point" title=3D"Boiling point">boiling point</a> of water can be affected q=
uite dramatically by raising or lowering the pressure), the triple point co=
ndition for a given substance can occur only at a single pressure and only =
at a single temperature. By the 1940s, the triple point of water had been e=
xperimentally measured to be about 0.6% of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Standard_atmosphere_(unit)" title=3D"Standard atmosphere (unit)">s=
tandard atmospheric pressure</a> and very close to 0.01&nbsp;=C2=B0C per th=
e historical definition of Celsius then in use.
</p><p>In 1948, the Celsius scale was recalibrated by assigning the triple =
point temperature of water the value of 0.01&nbsp;=C2=B0C exactly<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-:0_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-:0-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and allowing the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melting_point" title=3D"Melting point">melting poin=
t</a> at standard atmospheric pressure to have an empirically determined va=
lue (and the actual melting point at ambient pressure to have a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low-pressure_area" title=3D"Low-pressure area=
">fluctuating</a> value) close to 0&nbsp;=C2=B0C. This was justified on the=
 grounds that the triple point was judged to give a more accurately reprodu=
cible reference temperature than the melting point.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CGPM=
_9_res_3_(1948)_36-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-CGPM_9_res_3_(1948)-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The triple poi=
nt could be measured with =C2=B10.0001&nbsp;=C2=B0C accuracy, while the mel=
ting point just to =C2=B10.001&nbsp;=C2=B0C.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_35-1" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note=
-:0-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1954, with absolute zero having been experimentally determined to=
 be about =E2=88=92273.15&nbsp;=C2=B0C per the definition of =C2=B0C then i=
n use, Resolution&nbsp;3 of the 10th <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/General_Conference_on_Weights_and_Measures" title=3D"General Conference =
on Weights and Measures">General Conference on Weights and Measures</a> (CG=
PM) introduced a new internationally standardized Kelvin scale which define=
d the triple point as exactly 273.15 + 0.01 =3D 273.16 degrees Kelvin.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-CGPM_10_res_3_(1954)_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-CGPM_10_res_3_(1954)-37"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-res310_38-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-res310-38"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1967/1968, Resolution&nbsp;3 of the 13th CGPM renamed the unit in=
crement of thermodynamic temperature "kelvin", symbol K, replacing "degree =
Kelvin", symbol =C2=B0K.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CGPM_13_res_3_(1967)_39-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-C=
GPM_13_res_3_(1967)-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-res313_40-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-re=
s313-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Westphal_1952_41-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-Westphal_195=
2-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> The 13th CGPM also held in Resolution&nbsp;4 that "The ke=
lvin, unit of thermodynamic temperature, is equal to the fraction <link rel=
=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r121440203=
5"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">=
1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">273.16</span></=
span>=E2=81=A0</span> of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point =
of water."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST_SI_redefinition_4-1" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-NIST_SI_redefini=
tion-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-CGPM_13_res_4_(1967)_42-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-CGPM_13=
_res_4_(1967)-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-res413_43-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-res413-43"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>After <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre#Speed_of_light_=
definition" title=3D"Metre">the 1983 redefinition of the metre</a>, this le=
ft the kelvin, the second, and the kilogram as the only SI units not define=
d with reference to any other unit.
</p><p>In 2005, noting that the triple point could be influenced by the iso=
topic ratio of the hydrogen and oxygen making up a water sample and that th=
is was "now one of the major sources of the observed variability between di=
fferent realizations of the water triple point", the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Committee_for_Weights_and_Measures" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International Committee for Weights and Measures"=
>International Committee for Weights and Measures</a> (CIPM), a committee o=
f the CGPM, affirmed that for the purposes of delineating the temperature o=
f the triple point of water, the definition of the kelvin would refer to wa=
ter having the isotopic composition specified for <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Vienna_Standard_Mean_Ocean_Water" title=3D"Vienna Standard =
Mean Ocean Water">Vienna Standard Mean Ocean Water</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
NIST_SI_redefinition_4-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-NIST_SI_redefinition-4"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-CGPM_23_res_10_(2007)_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-CGPM_23_res_10_(2007)-44"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-sib2115_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-sib2115-45"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"2019_redefinition">2019 red=
efinition</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKe=
lvin&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: 2019 redefin=
ition"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_revision=
_of_the_SI" title=3D"2019 revision of the SI">2019 revision of the SI</a></=
div>
<figure class=3D"skin-invert-image" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Unit_relations_in_the_new_SI_black_arrows_t=
o_K.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia=
.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Unit_relations_in_the_new_SI_black_arrows=
_to_K.svg/330px-Unit_relations_in_the_new_SI_black_arrows_to_K.svg.png" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"280" height=3D"269" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"625" data-file-height=3D"600"></a><figcaption>2019 SI unit d=
ependencies. The kelvin (K) is now fixed in terms of the Boltzmann constant=
 (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i><sub>B</sub></span>) and the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joule" title=3D"Joule">joule</a>. The joule is=
 not shown because it is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_deri=
ved_unit" title=3D"SI derived unit">derived unit</a> defined by the metre (=
m), second (s), and kilogram (kg). Those SI base units are themselves defin=
ed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_constant" title=
=3D"Physical constant">universal constants</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speed_of_light" title=3D"Speed of light">speed of light=
</a> (<i><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>=
</i>), the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caesium_standard" title=
=3D"Caesium standard">caesium-133 hyperfine transition frequency</a> (<span=
 class=3D"texhtml">=CE=94<i>=CE=BD</i><sub>Cs</sub></span>) and the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planck_constant" title=3D"Planck constant=
">Planck constant</a> (<i><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">h</span></i>). Black arrows trace the dependencies from these cons=
tants to the kelvin.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boltzmann_constant" title=
=3D"Boltzmann constant">Boltzmann constant</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k=
</i><sub>B</sub></span> serves as the bridge in the relation <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>E</i> =3D <i>k</i><sub>B</sub><i>T</i></span>, linking charact=
eristic microscopic energies to the macroscopic temperature scale.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Kalinin_46-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-Kalinin-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the International =
System of Units (SI), the kelvin has traditionally been treated as an indep=
endent base unit with its own dimension. By contrast, in fundamental physic=
s it is common to adopt <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_un=
it" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Natural unit">natural units</a> by setti=
ng the Boltzmann constant equal to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/1" title=3D"1">unity</a>, so that temperature and energy share the same un=
its.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kalinin_46-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-Kalinin-46"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K=
elvin#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 2005, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_=
Committee_for_Weights_and_Measures" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Internat=
ional Committee for Weights and Measures">CIPM</a> began a programme to red=
efine the kelvin in terms of the Boltzmann constant, alongside exploring ne=
w definitions for several other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI=
_base_units" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI base units">SI base units</a=
> in terms of fundamental constants. The motivation was to allow more accur=
ate measurements at temperatures far away from the triple point of water, a=
nd to be independent from any particular substance or measurement.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Fischer2007_48-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-Fischer2007-48"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Originally sl=
ated for adoption in 2011 with the Boltzmann constant being <span class=3D"=
nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6977138064999999999=E2=99=A0"></span>1.380=
<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">65</span><i>X</i><span style=3D"margin-l=
eft:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9223</sup>&nbsp=
;J/K</span>, <i>X</i> to be determined,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-draft_49-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-d=
raft-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> concerns arose about maintaining the precision of the =
triple point, and the redefinition was postponed until such time as more ac=
curate measurements could be made, with these experiments taking several ye=
ars in some cases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvi=
n#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Ultimately, the kelvin redefinition became part=
 of the larger <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_revision_of_th=
e_SI" title=3D"2019 revision of the SI">2019 revision of the SI</a>. In lat=
e 2018, the 26th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) adopted =
the value of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i><sub>B</sub></span>&nbsp;=3D&n=
bsp;<span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6977138064900000000=E2=
=99=A0"></span>1.380<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">649</span><span styl=
e=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=92=
23</sup>&nbsp;J=E2=8B=85K<sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span><span style=3D"visibil=
ity:hidden; color:transparent; padding-left:2px">=E2=80=8D</span><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-physconst-k_52-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-physconst-k-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-draft_49-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Kelvin#cite_note-draft-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-MEP_for_kelvin_2=
019_1-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvi=
n#cite_note-MEP_for_kelvin_2019-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-SI_Brochur=
e_9_2-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvi=
n#cite_note-SI_Brochure_9-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST_SI_redefini=
tion_4-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelv=
in#cite_note-NIST_SI_redefinition-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-CGPM_26_=
res_1_(2018)_53-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-CGPM_26_res_1_(2018)-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the new defi=
nition officially came into force on 20 May 2019, the 144th anniversary of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre_Convention" title=3D"Met=
re Convention">Metre Convention</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CGPM_26_res_1_(2018=
)_53-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin=
#cite_note-CGPM_26_res_1_(2018)-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-MEP_for_=
kelvin_2019_1-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Kelvin#cite_note-MEP_for_kelvin_2019-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-SI=
_Brochure_9_2-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Kelvin#cite_note-SI_Brochure_9-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST_SI_=
redefinition_4-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Kelvin#cite_note-NIST_SI_redefinition-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>With this new definition, the kelvin now only depends on the Boltzma=
nn constant and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_constant"=
 title=3D"Physical constant">universal constants</a> (see 2019 SI unit depe=
ndencies diagram), allowing the kelvin to be expressed as:<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-SI_Brochure_9_2-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-SI_Brochure_9-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
