<p>In practical terms, as was the goal,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Fischer2007_48-1=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_=
note-Fischer2007-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the change went largely unnoticed: the cho=
sen value has enough accuracy and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Significant_figures" title=3D"Significant figures">significant figures</a> =
for continuity, ensuring that water still freezes at 0 =C2=B0C to high prec=
ision.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The difference lies in the=
 status of reference points. Before the redefinition, the triple point of w=
ater was taken as exact, while the Boltzmann constant had a measured value =
of <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6977138064903000000=E2=
=99=A0"></span>1.380<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">649</span><span styl=
e=3D"margin-left:.25em;">03</span>(51)<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;mar=
gin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9223</sup>&nbsp;J/K</span>, w=
ith a relative standard uncertainty of <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-so=
rt-value=3D"6993370000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>3.7<span style=3D"margin-l=
eft:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=927</sup></span=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-codata2017_55-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-codata2017-55"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Afterw=
ard, the Boltzmann constant was exact and the uncertainty is transferred to=
 the triple point of water, which is now <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-=
sort-value=3D"7002273160000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>273.1600(1)&nbsp;K</span=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-uncertainty_57-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-uncertainty-57"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On a deeper level, the kelvin is now defined in terms of the joule, =
making the separate existence of a temperature dimension theoretically unne=
cessary. The kelvin could have been redefined as a non-coherent derived SI =
unit, with <span class=3D"texhtml">1 K =3D <span class=3D"nowrap"><span dat=
a-sort-value=3D"6977138064900000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.380<span style=3D"ma=
rgin-left:.25em;">649</span><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:=
0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9223</sup>&nbsp;J</span></span>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Kalinin_46-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-Kalinin-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-58=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_=
note-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> Yet, "for historical and especially practical reasons,=
 the kelvin will continue to be a base unit of the SI".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
59" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cit=
e_note-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Practical_uses">Practical u=
ses</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKelvin&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Practical uses"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Kelvin_Temperature_Chart_Vertical_tightened.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descr=
iption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/=
1a/Kelvin_Temperature_Chart_Vertical_tightened.svg/120px-Kelvin_Temperature=
_Chart_Vertical_tightened.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"118" height=
=3D"390" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"380" data-file-height=
=3D"1256"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colour_t=
emperature" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Colour temperature">Colour tempe=
rature</a> (right) of various light sources (left)</figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Colour_temperature">Colour =
temperature</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Kelvin&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Colour te=
mperature"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stefan%E2%80%93Boltzmann=
_constant" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stefan=E2=80=93Boltzmann constant=
">Stefan=E2=80=93Boltzmann constant</a></div>
<p>The kelvin is often used as a measure of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Colour_temperature" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Colour tem=
perature">colour temperature</a> of light sources. Colour temperature is ba=
sed upon the principle that a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blac=
k_body" title=3D"Black body">black body</a> radiator emits light with a fre=
quency distribution characteristic of its temperature. Black bodies at temp=
eratures below about <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"700340=
0000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>4000&nbsp;K</span> appear reddish, whereas t=
hose above about <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003750000=
000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>7500&nbsp;K</span> appear bluish. Colour tempera=
ture is important in the fields of image projection and photography, where =
a colour temperature of approximately <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sor=
t-value=3D"7003560000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>5600&nbsp;K</span> is requi=
red to match "daylight" film emulsions.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomy" title=3D"Astr=
onomy">astronomy</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stellar_=
classification" title=3D"Stellar classification">stellar classification</a>=
 of stars and their place on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H=
ertzsprung%E2%80%93Russell_diagram" title=3D"Hertzsprung=E2=80=93Russell di=
agram">Hertzsprung=E2=80=93Russell diagram</a> are based, in part, upon the=
ir surface temperature, known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
ffective_temperature" title=3D"Effective temperature">effective temperature=
</a>. The photosphere of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun" =
title=3D"Sun">Sun</a>, for instance, has an effective temperature of <span =
class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003577200000000000=E2=99=A0"></s=
pan>5772&nbsp;K</span><sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Kelvin#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-62"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> as adopted by IAU 2015 Resolu=
tion B3.
</p><p>Digital cameras and photographic software often use colour temperatu=
re in K in edit and setup menus. The simple guide is that higher colour tem=
perature produces an image with enhanced white and blue hues. The reduction=
 in colour temperature produces an image more dominated by reddish, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color_theory#Warm_vs._cool_colors" title=
=3D"Color theory">"warmer" colours</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Kelvin_as_a_unit_of_noise_t=
emperature">Kelvin as a unit of noise temperature</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKelvin&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Kelvin as a unit of noise temperature"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noise_figure" title=
=3D"Noise figure">Noise figure</a></div>
<p>For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronics" title=3D"Elect=
ronics">electronics</a>, the kelvin is used as an indicator of how <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_noise" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Electronic noise">noisy</a> a circuit is in relation to an ultimate=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noise_floor" title=3D"Noise floor=
">noise floor</a>, i.e. the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noise_=
temperature" title=3D"Noise temperature">noise temperature</a>. The <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnson%E2%80%93Nyquist_noise" title=3D"J=
ohnson=E2=80=93Nyquist noise">Johnson=E2=80=93Nyquist noise</a> of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resistors" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Resistors">resistors</a> (which produces an associated <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnson%E2%80%93Nyquist_noise#Thermal_noise_on_capaci=
tors" title=3D"Johnson=E2=80=93Nyquist noise"><i>kTC</i> noise</a> when com=
bined with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capacitors" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Capacitors">capacitors</a>) is a type of thermal noise =
derived from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boltzmann_constan=
t" title=3D"Boltzmann constant">Boltzmann constant</a> and can be used to d=
etermine the noise temperature of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Electrical_network" title=3D"Electrical network">circuit</a> using the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friis_formulas_for_noise" title=3D"F=
riis formulas for noise">Friis formulas for noise</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Derived_units_and_SI_multip=
les">Derived units and SI multiples</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DKelvin&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D=
"Edit section: Derived units and SI multiples"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orders_of_magnitude_=
(temperature)" title=3D"Orders of magnitude (temperature)">Orders of magnit=
ude (temperature)</a></div>
<p>The only <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_derived_unit#Derive=
d_units_with_special_names" title=3D"SI derived unit">SI derived unit with =
a special name</a> derived from the kelvin is the degree Celsius. Like othe=
r SI units, the kelvin can also be modified by adding a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_prefix" title=3D"Metric prefix">metric prefix<=
/a> that multiplies it by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_=
of_10" title=3D"Power of 10">power of 10</a>:
</p>
