<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Orthography">Orthography</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKelvin&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Orthography"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>According to SI convention, the kelvin is never referred to nor written =
as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degree_(temperature)" title=
=3D"Degree (temperature)"><i>degree</i></a>. The word "kelvin" is not capit=
alized when used as a unit. It may be in plural form as appropriate (for ex=
ample, "it is 283 kelvins outside", as for "it is 50 degrees Fahrenheit" an=
d "10 degrees Celsius").<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nist_intro_5-2" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-nist_intro-5=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-plurals_64-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-plurals-64"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-65" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-66"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> The unit's symbol K is a capital letter,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CGPM_=
13_res_3_(1967)_39-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-CGPM_13_res_3_(1967)-39"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> per the SI co=
nvention to capitalize symbols of units derived from the name of a person.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is common convention to capita=
lize Kelvin when referring to Lord Kelvin<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nist_intro_5-3=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_=
note-nist_intro-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or the Kelvin scale.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin#cite_not=
e-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The unit symbol K is encoded in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Unicode" title=3D"Unicode">Unicode</a> at code point <span class=3D"no=
wrap"><span class=3D"monospaced">U+212A</span> </span><span style=3D"font-s=
ize:125%;line-height:1em">=E2=84=AA</span> <span style=3D"font-variant: sma=
ll-caps; text-transform: lowercase; font-feature-settings: 'onum'">KELVIN S=
IGN</span>. However, this is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uni=
code_compatibility_characters" title=3D"Unicode compatibility characters">c=
ompatibility character</a> provided for compatibility with legacy encodings=
. The Unicode standard recommends using <span class=3D"nowrap"><link rel=3D=
"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"><=
span class=3D"monospaced">U+004B</span> </span><span style=3D"font-size:125=
%;line-height:1em">K</span> <span style=3D"font-variant: small-caps; text-t=
ransform: lowercase; font-feature-settings: 'onum'">LATIN CAPITAL LETTER K<=
/span> instead; that is, a normal capital <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/K" title=3D"K">K</a>. "Three letterlike symbols have been given can=
onical equivalence to regular letters: <span class=3D"nowrap"><link rel=3D"=
mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"><s=
pan class=3D"monospaced">U+2126</span> </span><span style=3D"font-size:125%=
;line-height:1em">=E2=84=A6</span> <span style=3D"font-variant: small-caps;=
 text-transform: lowercase; font-feature-settings: 'onum'">OHM SIGN</span>,=
 <span class=3D"nowrap"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"=
mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"><span class=3D"monospaced">U+212A</span>=
 </span><span style=3D"font-size:125%;line-height:1em">=E2=84=AA</span> <sp=
an style=3D"font-variant: small-caps; text-transform: lowercase; font-featu=
re-settings: 'onum'">KELVIN SIGN</span>, and <span class=3D"nowrap"><link r=
el=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r8860497=
